00:38:13.240 --> 00:38:15.190
if you already touched on this.

00:38:15.190 --> 00:38:19.010
But I heard you mention Zika
briefly during your talk.

00:38:19.010 --> 00:38:20.560
So I was just
wondering, do you feel

00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:23.230
like was the Olympics--
do you think that could

00:38:23.230 --> 00:38:25.080
be a big factor in its spread?

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:28.170
Or in the big picture, it
doesn't really matter much?

00:38:28.170 --> 00:38:30.000
SONIA SHAH: So Zika
virus is carried

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:32.520
by Aedes aegypti mosquitoes.

00:38:32.520 --> 00:38:37.360
In August, it'll be winter
in the southern hemisphere.

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:42.950
So this mosquito is very
sensitive to climatic factors.

00:38:42.950 --> 00:38:46.050
It needs at least a week
or two of standing water

00:38:46.050 --> 00:38:47.720
in order for the eggs to hatch.

00:38:47.720 --> 00:38:50.320
And then for one
mosquito to get infected,

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:52.280
it takes a blood meal.

00:38:52.280 --> 00:38:54.810
And then it takes another
week for the virus

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:57.700
to kind of mature into its
life cycle in the mosquito

00:38:57.700 --> 00:39:01.470
before the mosquito can bite
another person and pass it on.

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:05.184
So if it's dry, if it's
cool, and mosquitoes either

00:39:05.184 --> 00:39:07.350
don't hatch-- there's a lot
of standing water around

00:39:07.350 --> 00:39:08.570
for mosquitoes to
hatch-- or if they

00:39:08.570 --> 00:39:10.430
don't live as long,
because when it's dry,

00:39:10.430 --> 00:39:13.230
they desiccate
really easily, that

00:39:13.230 --> 00:39:15.930
is going to dramatically
reduce mosquito populations.

00:39:15.930 --> 00:39:18.750
And that's the conditions that
they're expecting in August.

00:39:18.750 --> 00:39:21.321
Of course, we're living in
a time of disruptive weather

00:39:21.321 --> 00:39:21.820
patterns.

00:39:21.820 --> 00:39:23.780
And all you would
need is a couple weeks

00:39:23.780 --> 00:39:27.870
of standing water around in,
like I said tiny, tiny bits.

00:39:27.870 --> 00:39:30.530
Because the eggs of
the aegypti mosquito--

00:39:30.530 --> 00:39:33.395
they desiccate, and then they're
all over the environment.

00:39:33.395 --> 00:39:35.520
And as soon as you just
put a little water on them,

00:39:35.520 --> 00:39:36.478
they come back to life.

00:39:36.478 --> 00:39:40.100
Because they can be dormant
for weeks or even months.

00:39:40.100 --> 00:39:44.600
That said, we're not going to
stop Zika from coming here,

00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:46.610
whether we go to
the Olympics or not.

00:39:46.610 --> 00:39:50.370
We have millions of Americans
going back and forth.

00:39:50.370 --> 00:39:52.880
And we Zika's
probably already here

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:56.350
in a larger proportion
than we actually know.

00:39:56.350 --> 00:39:58.680
Because of course, 80%
of people who get it

00:39:58.680 --> 00:40:00.130
don't have any symptoms.

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:03.590
So we have a lot of silent
carriers who can travel.

00:40:03.590 --> 00:40:06.430
And they'll never know that
they were infected at all.

00:40:06.430 --> 00:40:09.040
And even the people
who do have symptoms,

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:11.917
it's so mild that you wouldn't
necessarily get diagnosed.

00:40:11.917 --> 00:40:14.250
You would just think, oh, I
have a rash, a little fever.

00:40:14.250 --> 00:40:14.830
It passes.

00:40:14.830 --> 00:40:16.925
It's self limiting.

00:40:16.925 --> 00:40:17.800
So it's very cryptic.

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:19.030
It can travel really far.

00:40:19.030 --> 00:40:21.940
So whether we go or not,
Zika's going to come.

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:25.010
And it's probably already here.

00:40:25.010 --> 00:40:26.019
Thanks.

