00:41:45.302 --> 00:41:47.260
and how outbreaks occur,
that we could actually

00:41:47.260 --> 00:41:50.360
have a forecasting for
disease-- a disease

00:41:50.360 --> 00:41:52.000
forecast so you could
know in advance.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.130
And that means
everything, because time

00:41:54.130 --> 00:41:55.530
is completely of
the essence when

00:41:55.530 --> 00:41:59.260
you think of these things
that can spread exponentially.

00:41:59.260 --> 00:42:02.280
So if you know even days
or weeks in advance,

00:42:02.280 --> 00:42:04.570
there's so much more
we can do to save lives

00:42:04.570 --> 00:42:07.540
and to prevent all the
destruction of these outbreaks.

00:42:07.540 --> 00:42:09.790
So I think there's lots of
opportunities in that area,

00:42:09.790 --> 00:42:10.290
especially.

00:42:12.884 --> 00:42:13.550
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:42:13.550 --> 00:42:16.370
Sounds like antibiotic
has been a big problem.

00:42:16.370 --> 00:42:19.776
And seems that over
70% of antibiotics

00:42:19.776 --> 00:42:23.390
are used on livestock.

00:42:23.390 --> 00:42:28.590
So how do you think we
can tackle this problem?

00:42:28.590 --> 00:42:30.470
SONIA SHAH: Well, we
know that in places

00:42:30.470 --> 00:42:33.560
where they don't use
antibiotics commercially,

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:35.940
and antibiotics are used
as they say rationally--

00:42:35.940 --> 00:42:38.356
which is only when they're
medically necessary-- that they

00:42:38.356 --> 00:42:41.140
don't have problems with
antibiotic-resistant bacteria.

00:42:41.140 --> 00:42:43.380
So that is a known thing.

00:42:43.380 --> 00:42:45.920
So the path forward is
actually really clear.

00:42:45.920 --> 00:42:47.680
We need to use these
drugs rationally.

00:42:47.680 --> 00:42:49.460
We need to steward these drugs.

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:50.670
We have not done that.

00:42:50.670 --> 00:42:52.140
We've used them as commodities.

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:53.910
And so that's the thing.

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:56.690
The thing we have to
do is really simple.

00:42:56.690 --> 00:42:59.030
It's difficult
politically, of course.

00:42:59.030 --> 00:43:02.300
So that's going to
be the big hurdle.

00:43:02.300 --> 00:43:05.000
And what we've seen
with Obama's recent--

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:08.740
the White House
recently passed--

00:43:08.740 --> 00:43:11.120
they made some efforts,
some initiatives to try

00:43:11.120 --> 00:43:12.700
to deal with this problem.

00:43:12.700 --> 00:43:14.750
And there's two parts to it.

00:43:14.750 --> 00:43:19.250
One part was let's try to reduce
use and use these rationally.

00:43:19.250 --> 00:43:21.660
But first let's get
a committee to think

00:43:21.660 --> 00:43:23.840
about it for a couple
years, and then

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:25.120
issues and recommendations.

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:27.170
On the other hand, the
other thing we can do

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:29.310
is, let's throw a lot of
money at drug companies

00:43:29.310 --> 00:43:30.722
to come up with new antibiotics.

00:43:30.722 --> 00:43:33.180
And then we can just keep using
them like as badly as we're

00:43:33.180 --> 00:43:34.010
using them now.

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:36.440
But we'll just keep getting
new ones and getting new ones

00:43:36.440 --> 00:43:38.120
and getting new ones.

00:43:38.120 --> 00:43:40.120
Right now, drug
companies don't want

00:43:40.120 --> 00:43:43.140
to create a lot of
antibiotics, because it's not

00:43:43.140 --> 00:43:43.970
a very good market.

00:43:43.970 --> 00:43:48.740
I mean, these are drugs you only
use for a week or two at most.

00:43:48.740 --> 00:43:53.170
And people have been trained
to only want to pay $100 or so.

00:43:53.170 --> 00:43:55.420
I mean, we'll pay hundreds
of thousands of dollars

00:43:55.420 --> 00:43:57.680
for a cancer drug
that maybe will

00:43:57.680 --> 00:43:59.950
extend life for a week at best.

00:43:59.950 --> 00:44:02.560
But a lifesaving
antibiotic, we don't

00:44:02.560 --> 00:44:03.800
want to pay more than $100.

00:44:03.800 --> 00:44:06.120
So it's not a very
good market for them.

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:08.259
So that's one of the
parts of the initiative,

00:44:08.259 --> 00:44:10.300
is to throw more money
and incentives at the drug

00:44:10.300 --> 00:44:11.758
companies, so that
they'll actually

00:44:11.758 --> 00:44:13.310
make us some new antibiotics.

00:44:13.310 --> 00:44:14.270
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:44:14.270 --> 00:44:16.320
SONIA SHAH: Thank you.

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:17.160
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:44:17.160 --> 00:44:19.800
I've been reading in some
journals and articles

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:24.910
about the possibility of
having male mosquitoes which

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:27.210
are infertile, and introducing
them to the population

00:44:27.210 --> 00:44:30.670
and trying to cut back
on mosquito populations.

00:44:30.670 --> 00:44:32.560
Do you think that's
a viable solution

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:34.160
to cut back on mosquitoes?

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:37.379
Or do you think that's
kind of a stretch?

00:44:37.379 --> 00:44:39.170
SONIA SHAH: I mean,
this is the thing-- you

00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:40.690
introduce an infertile male.

00:44:40.690 --> 00:44:42.380
And then it mates.

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:44.270
And they so they have no babies.

00:44:44.270 --> 00:44:46.100
So you've done that once.

00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:48.530
Now, that trait is not
going to get passed down.

00:44:48.530 --> 00:44:51.580
So there's no like
sustainable chain of events.

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:53.140
You have just keep
doing this-- keep

00:44:53.140 --> 00:44:55.920
introducing more and
more of these insects

00:44:55.920 --> 00:44:58.934
in order to keep controlling
the population of mosquitoes.

00:44:58.934 --> 00:45:01.100
So in that sense, it's not
that different than using

00:45:01.100 --> 00:45:02.480
insecticides.

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:05.790
And what we know, that when
we throw killing chemicals

00:45:05.790 --> 00:45:08.950
or reduce the ability of
living things to reproduce,

00:45:08.950 --> 00:45:11.800
that they evolve in ways so
that they can get around that.

00:45:11.800 --> 00:45:15.760
Because there's very strong
selection for creatures

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:17.210
to do that.

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:20.960
So to me, it's as promising
as a new insecticide.

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:23.180
It's not any more
promising than that.

00:45:23.180 --> 00:45:24.930
And then you have all
the ethical problems

00:45:24.930 --> 00:45:27.100
of places where
they already have

00:45:27.100 --> 00:45:30.140
a lot of mosquito-borne disease,
and then people coming up,

00:45:30.140 --> 00:45:32.000
white-coated people
coming up and releasing

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:35.460
more mosquitoes that
are special-- there's

00:45:35.460 --> 00:45:37.140
going to be some
resistance to that,

00:45:37.140 --> 00:45:39.210
I think, in local communities.

00:45:39.210 --> 00:45:40.403
That could be an issue.

00:45:42.962 --> 00:45:44.920
The other thing is a lot
of these diseases that

00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:47.170
are caused by
mosquitoes, you don't

00:45:47.170 --> 00:45:50.930
have to kill a lot of
mosquitoes to control them.

00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:53.400
There's usually a time
period during which

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:58.359
the disease or pathogen inside
the mosquito has to develop,

00:45:58.359 --> 00:45:59.400
has to have a life cycle.

00:45:59.400 --> 00:46:01.120
So malaria takes
seven to 10 days.

00:46:01.120 --> 00:46:03.700
Zika takes around the
same amount of time.

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:05.200
So you don't need
to kill them all.

00:46:05.200 --> 00:46:07.870
You just need to
shorten their lives.

00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:10.400
So if you just depress
the lifespan of mosquitoes

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:15.600
so that they don't live long
enough to pass on a pathogen,

00:46:15.600 --> 00:46:19.150
then you can disrupt the
disease spread altogether.

00:46:19.150 --> 00:46:22.207
And you won't be working
against evolution.

00:46:22.207 --> 00:46:24.040
Because you're going
to allow these mosquito

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:25.250
populations to survive.

00:46:25.250 --> 00:46:27.030
You're going to allow
them to reproduce.

00:46:27.030 --> 00:46:29.446
You're just going to kill all
the grandmothers, basically.

