00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:28.690
more insecticides to
depress mosquito populations

00:49:28.690 --> 00:49:31.600
in the South and other the
parts of the United States

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:34.550
where we have Aedes mosquitoes
that could carry Zika virus.

00:49:34.550 --> 00:49:36.866
And the fact is, it's
already too late to do that,

00:49:36.866 --> 00:49:38.490
because these
populations of mosquitoes

00:49:38.490 --> 00:49:40.540
are highly entrenched.

00:49:40.540 --> 00:49:42.980
Their eggs are everywhere
in the environment.

00:49:42.980 --> 00:49:45.470
You could maybe depress their
populations for a while,

00:49:45.470 --> 00:49:47.710
but you're not going to
get rid of them anymore.

00:49:47.710 --> 00:49:49.710
And it's an interesting
story of what happened--

00:49:49.710 --> 00:49:51.440
how we got these mosquitoes.

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:53.820
Both of the Aedes mosquitoes
that are in this country

00:49:53.820 --> 00:49:55.660
are invasive species.

00:49:55.660 --> 00:49:59.670
Aedes albopictus, which
is the one that about 60%

00:49:59.670 --> 00:50:02.210
of the United States
is vulnerable to--

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:04.650
and I live in Baltimore, and
there's tons of these things

00:50:04.650 --> 00:50:04.930
around.

00:50:04.930 --> 00:50:06.050
And you guys have
them up here, too,

00:50:06.050 --> 00:50:07.966
I think when it's hot,
like in the summer when

00:50:07.966 --> 00:50:09.930
it's really hot.

00:50:09.930 --> 00:50:12.620
That's an invasive mosquito
that came over in the used tire

00:50:12.620 --> 00:50:16.010
trade in the 1970s and 1980s.

00:50:16.010 --> 00:50:19.480
And people are bringing tires.

00:50:19.480 --> 00:50:21.509
In the wild, they
live in tree holes.

00:50:21.509 --> 00:50:23.050
These mosquitoes
live in tree holes--

00:50:23.050 --> 00:50:27.280
so a dark environment
with standing water.

00:50:27.280 --> 00:50:28.800
And you think about a tire.

00:50:28.800 --> 00:50:30.970
I mean, you can never get
the water out of a tire.

00:50:30.970 --> 00:50:33.380
So these used tires
fill up with some water.

00:50:33.380 --> 00:50:36.840
And the mosquitoes lay
their eggs in there.

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:41.270
And they survive this long
travel across from Asia.

00:50:41.270 --> 00:50:44.920
We have distributed these
tires across the nation.

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:48.060
I mean, they're used
for embankments.

00:50:48.060 --> 00:50:49.870
People throw them
over into streams

00:50:49.870 --> 00:50:52.900
to build up the
streambeds for erosion.

00:50:52.900 --> 00:50:56.890
They're recapped and then
put back into rotation.

00:50:56.890 --> 00:50:59.580
They're also often
kept in giant piles

00:50:59.580 --> 00:51:01.980
next to other giant piles
that have been sitting there

00:51:01.980 --> 00:51:02.910
for a long time.

00:51:02.910 --> 00:51:06.070
So even if they didn't come over
infested with these mosquito

00:51:06.070 --> 00:51:09.740
eggs, they will get infested
while they're sitting there.

00:51:09.740 --> 00:51:12.730
And so that's been
going on for decades.

00:51:12.730 --> 00:51:16.210
And this happened with
the full knowledge

00:51:16.210 --> 00:51:18.460
of our medical entomologists
and our medical community

00:51:18.460 --> 00:51:20.226
that this was happening.

00:51:20.226 --> 00:51:22.100
So that was the time
when we should have been

00:51:22.100 --> 00:51:23.224
doing the mosquito control.

00:51:23.224 --> 00:51:26.060
That was the time when we should
have said, let's quarantine,

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:28.240
inspect, and treat these tires.

00:51:28.240 --> 00:51:31.180
Because the US military actually
knew that this was happening.

00:51:31.180 --> 00:51:35.670
It started in the 1940s when
all of our surplus war materials

00:51:35.670 --> 00:51:37.400
were coming back from
war zones in Asia.

00:51:37.400 --> 00:51:40.200
And they found the tires were
just full of all these mosquito

00:51:40.200 --> 00:51:40.820
eggs.

00:51:40.820 --> 00:51:43.030
And so they started
treating them

00:51:43.030 --> 00:51:45.940
so it wouldn't lead to an
invasion of these populations.

00:51:45.940 --> 00:51:47.950
But once private
companies started

00:51:47.950 --> 00:51:51.090
doing this, and bringing these
tires in container ships-- not

00:51:51.090 --> 00:51:53.880
just a ship, but
these giant containers

00:51:53.880 --> 00:51:58.130
and many, many containers--
we just didn't do it.

00:51:58.130 --> 00:52:00.110
So we totally dropped the ball.

00:52:00.110 --> 00:52:02.590
That's when the mosquito
control should have happened.

00:52:02.590 --> 00:52:04.880
At this point, I
wonder, actually,

00:52:04.880 --> 00:52:09.500
if immunity isn't our
best defense against Zika.

00:52:09.500 --> 00:52:12.710
Once you get Zika, it looks
like you don't get it again.

00:52:12.710 --> 00:52:15.000
That's what the science
looks like right now.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.630
Of course, a lot more
needs to be learned.

00:52:17.630 --> 00:52:20.579
But given that it is mild--
if you have your bout of Zika,

00:52:20.579 --> 00:52:22.620
you may not even know you
have your bout of Zika.

00:52:22.620 --> 00:52:24.489
But after that, you're immune.

00:52:24.489 --> 00:52:25.530
Then you can have babies.

00:52:25.530 --> 00:52:28.110
You can have sex,
do all these things.

00:52:28.110 --> 00:52:31.330
You're not going to
endanger the child.

00:52:31.330 --> 00:52:33.360
That's, of course,
the biggest risk.

00:52:33.360 --> 00:52:35.930
So if we want to
build up immunity,

00:52:35.930 --> 00:52:37.250
then it's a real question.

00:52:37.250 --> 00:52:39.920
Should we depress
mosquito populations?

00:52:39.920 --> 00:52:42.700
Because doesn't that mean
that fewer people are going

00:52:42.700 --> 00:52:44.250
to get exposed to this virus?

00:52:44.250 --> 00:52:48.620
I mean, if we all are able to
put off childbearing while we

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:51.170
develop immunity, or
protect our pregnant women

00:52:51.170 --> 00:52:52.670
and protect our
childbearing people,

00:52:52.670 --> 00:52:57.190
and let everybody
else get immunity--

00:52:57.190 --> 00:52:59.970
but it's sort of an
anathematic disease.

00:52:59.970 --> 00:53:02.480
It's just a totally
disruptive idea.

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:05.960
I mean, public health
authorities can't possibly say,

00:53:05.960 --> 00:53:07.680
oh, we're just going
to let Zika come.

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:09.528
Everyone can get infected.

00:53:09.528 --> 00:53:12.930
AUDIENCE: Say, hey, go to Puerto
Rico with your pregnant wife.

00:53:12.930 --> 00:53:14.360
SONIA SHAH: Well, exactly.

00:53:14.360 --> 00:53:16.920
And I think at the root
of it is sort of this idea

00:53:16.920 --> 00:53:21.010
that we shouldn't be
vulnerable to contagion.

00:53:21.010 --> 00:53:26.090
We had probably about 40
years from 1940 to 1980

00:53:26.090 --> 00:53:30.470
or so, when we felt like
contagions were under control.

00:53:30.470 --> 00:53:32.400
And we could live this
sort of germ-free life.

00:53:32.400 --> 00:53:34.820
And if we did get an infection,
we could just take something.

00:53:34.820 --> 00:53:36.660
And it'll be really
simple, and get over it.

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:41.050
And I think that has infiltrated
our thinking to such a degree

00:53:41.050 --> 00:53:43.850
that when there is these
threats that maybe aren't

00:53:43.850 --> 00:53:46.730
so bad for most of us--
I mean, most people are

00:53:46.730 --> 00:53:48.770
going to be fine with Zika.

00:53:48.770 --> 00:53:50.810
It's just really the
microcephaly in children

00:53:50.810 --> 00:53:52.300
that's the main thing.

00:53:52.300 --> 00:53:54.084
But we don't think
of it that way.

00:53:54.084 --> 00:53:55.250
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:53:55.250 --> 00:53:56.166
SONIA SHAH: Thank you.

00:53:59.889 --> 00:54:01.930
AUDIENCE: Overall great
speech, very informative.

00:54:01.930 --> 00:54:03.990
But the underlying
thing I've seen

00:54:03.990 --> 00:54:06.140
that it seems to be the
advancement of the economy

00:54:06.140 --> 00:54:11.480
that's really pushed this issue
of pandemics to the main stage,

00:54:11.480 --> 00:54:14.790
through transportation
or economic advancement,

00:54:14.790 --> 00:54:18.400
going into different areas
that weren't developed before.

00:54:18.400 --> 00:54:21.180
I mean, is there an
international coalition

00:54:21.180 --> 00:54:23.530
that's trying to create
standards to prevent this, when

00:54:23.530 --> 00:54:26.280
we actually have workers
going internationally

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:29.940
to different areas that never
have been inhabited or visited

00:54:29.940 --> 00:54:32.440
by humans ever,
to prevent spreads

00:54:32.440 --> 00:54:34.990
of different contagions?

00:54:34.990 --> 00:54:36.990
SONIA SHAH: So that would
be great if there was.

00:54:36.990 --> 00:54:38.190
But of course, there isn't.

00:54:38.190 --> 00:54:39.510
So this is all unregulated.

00:54:39.510 --> 00:54:41.470
People can do what they want.

00:54:41.470 --> 00:54:44.800
Some people go want to go in
Congo and start a mine there,

00:54:44.800 --> 00:54:46.894
they just get the
appropriate licensing

00:54:46.894 --> 00:54:49.060
from some corrupt governments,
and they can do that.

00:54:49.060 --> 00:54:51.830
So that's the world we live in.

00:54:51.830 --> 00:54:56.020
That said, economic
growth is still

00:54:56.020 --> 00:54:58.620
really important for
controlling contagions, too.

00:54:58.620 --> 00:55:01.880
We saw during the Ebola
outbreak in West Africa

00:55:01.880 --> 00:55:04.450
that a lot of other nations
got really panicked and scared,

00:55:04.450 --> 00:55:07.520
and started to cut down trade
and transportation links.

00:55:07.520 --> 00:55:10.570
And this had a terrible
effect on the ability

00:55:10.570 --> 00:55:13.250
of those countries to
control the disease.

00:55:13.250 --> 00:55:14.710
Aid workers couldn't come in.

00:55:14.710 --> 00:55:17.990
Commodities couldn't come in.

00:55:17.990 --> 00:55:20.350
These are fragile
economies to begin with,

00:55:20.350 --> 00:55:22.410
and they started
to really suffer.

00:55:22.410 --> 00:55:25.190
And that completely
undermines their ability

00:55:25.190 --> 00:55:26.420
to contain these pathogens.

00:55:26.420 --> 00:55:31.260
So it's not a one-to-one thing
that economic-- we need both.

00:55:31.260 --> 00:55:33.160
For getting rid of a
lot of these diseases,

00:55:33.160 --> 00:55:36.920
we need more development and
more prosperity-- diseases

00:55:36.920 --> 00:55:40.950
like malaria, which are very
much shaped by poverty-- just

00:55:40.950 --> 00:55:42.941
living in poor circumstances.

00:55:42.941 --> 00:55:44.190
You don't have window screens.

00:55:44.190 --> 00:55:46.780
You have bad drainage around.

00:55:46.780 --> 00:55:49.520
Lifting people out of poverty
through economic development

00:55:49.520 --> 00:55:52.817
would actually do a lot to
control a disease like that.

00:55:52.817 --> 00:55:54.400
AUDIENCE: I mean,
my question was more

00:55:54.400 --> 00:55:56.800
pushing towards there's
no measures that's

00:55:56.800 --> 00:55:58.920
done by the CDC.

00:55:58.920 --> 00:56:02.020
For instance, if you visited
Europe in set period,

00:56:02.020 --> 00:56:04.425
you can't give blood
because of mad cow.

00:56:04.425 --> 00:56:06.550
They don't have anything
for workers that come back

00:56:06.550 --> 00:56:09.890
internationally to screen
them properly medically,

00:56:09.890 --> 00:56:12.100
and make sure that they
don't have any of these--

00:56:12.100 --> 00:56:14.599
SONIA SHAH: I think there
probably is in an ad hoc way.

00:56:14.599 --> 00:56:16.640
But the problem is, we're
talking about pathogens

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:18.050
that we don't know about.

00:56:18.050 --> 00:56:20.890
So how do you screen for things
you don't know are there?

00:56:20.890 --> 00:56:23.010
We don't really have the
diagnostics to do that.

00:56:23.010 --> 00:56:26.880
So that piece of the puzzle
would be just technically

00:56:26.880 --> 00:56:27.948
impossible at the moment.

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:33.430
AUDIENCE: Thanks
for a great talk.

00:56:33.430 --> 00:56:35.770
So I think it's an
unfortunate truth

00:56:35.770 --> 00:56:37.670
that the private and
public interests that

00:56:37.670 --> 00:56:41.930
led to the cholera outbreak in
New York still exists today.

00:56:41.930 --> 00:56:46.350
So what do you think we didn't
do in the last 100 years

00:56:46.350 --> 00:56:49.483
that we should probably
not repeat in the next 100?

00:56:51.867 --> 00:56:53.450
SONIA SHAH: I mean,
I think there's so

00:56:53.450 --> 00:56:57.430
many lessons from the past that
are still applicable today.

00:56:57.430 --> 00:56:59.400
So that was sort
of my main point,

00:56:59.400 --> 00:57:03.480
is that all the ways in which
these old pandemics were

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:09.602
unfolding are still factors
today-- in fact, even more so.

00:57:09.602 --> 00:57:10.560
Is that what you meant?

00:57:10.560 --> 00:57:12.018
AUDIENCE: I'm
thinking mostly about

00:57:12.018 --> 00:57:13.890
the private-public interest.

00:57:13.890 --> 00:57:15.390
SONIA SHAH: So
what's happened now--

00:57:15.390 --> 00:57:19.280
and I think it's actually
a little more worrisome--

00:57:19.280 --> 00:57:23.390
is that we've divested
out of public health,

00:57:23.390 --> 00:57:24.830
to a large degree.

00:57:24.830 --> 00:57:27.730
The WHO, for
example-- we've been

00:57:27.730 --> 00:57:31.660
under-financing that agency
since about the '80s.

00:57:31.660 --> 00:57:35.500
Their budget has been getting
smaller and smaller every year

00:57:35.500 --> 00:57:38.330
in terms of their membership
dues from member countries.

00:57:38.330 --> 00:57:41.570
So what they've done is they've
turned to the private sector

00:57:41.570 --> 00:57:45.960
to do partnerships to
maintain their budget.

00:57:45.960 --> 00:57:48.480
So 80% or so of the
WHO budget is now

00:57:48.480 --> 00:57:50.580
coming from these donations.

00:57:50.580 --> 00:57:51.710
And that can be companies.

00:57:51.710 --> 00:57:52.690
It can be NGOs.

00:57:52.690 --> 00:57:54.190
It can be other governments.

00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:56.670
It can be any kind
of entity, really.

00:57:56.670 --> 00:57:59.690
But the problem is,
they earmark that money.

00:57:59.690 --> 00:58:04.510
So the WHO is not in charge
of the majority of its budget.

00:58:04.510 --> 00:58:07.570
Other entities are
in charge of that.

00:58:07.570 --> 00:58:09.370
And there is no
democratic accountability

00:58:09.370 --> 00:58:10.870
to what they decide.

00:58:10.870 --> 00:58:15.570
So we know that 91% of
those extra-budgetary funds,

00:58:15.570 --> 00:58:18.090
those donated funds
that the WHO gets--

00:58:18.090 --> 00:58:22.760
are given over to diseases that
affect 8% of the global disease

00:58:22.760 --> 00:58:23.520
burden.

00:58:23.520 --> 00:58:25.220
So it is a huge mismatch.

00:58:25.220 --> 00:58:27.760
So the WHO is not
able to really address

00:58:27.760 --> 00:58:30.810
our global health priorities
because of these budgeting

00:58:30.810 --> 00:58:31.520
issues.

00:58:31.520 --> 00:58:33.870
And we've seen it
even with CDC now.

00:58:33.870 --> 00:58:36.420
CDC is getting a lot more money
from private interests, too.

00:58:36.420 --> 00:58:37.920
They're doing whole
campaigns that

00:58:37.920 --> 00:58:41.710
are in partnership with drug
companies, and the sugar

00:58:41.710 --> 00:58:44.590
industry, and a whole
bunch of other companies,

00:58:44.590 --> 00:58:46.950
because that's how
they can continue

00:58:46.950 --> 00:58:48.240
doing some work at all.

00:58:48.240 --> 00:58:51.700
When the CDC tried to do gun
prevention violence research,

00:58:51.700 --> 00:58:53.750
the NRA just shut them down.

00:58:53.750 --> 00:58:57.470
And they slashed a whole
big part of their budget.

00:58:57.470 --> 00:59:00.040
So it's very difficult for
these public health agencies

00:59:00.040 --> 00:59:01.999
to tackle private interests.

00:59:01.999 --> 00:59:04.540
And what they've been doing more
and more just collaborating.

00:59:04.540 --> 00:59:06.780
So what we get is
public health-- we

00:59:06.780 --> 00:59:10.121
have the Venn diagram of things
we can do for public health,

00:59:10.121 --> 00:59:12.370
things we can do that will
protect economic interests,

00:59:12.370 --> 00:59:13.720
and there's that overlap.

00:59:13.720 --> 00:59:15.120
And that's what
our public health

00:59:15.120 --> 00:59:16.660
community is able to do today.

00:59:16.660 --> 00:59:19.740
But all those other things that
kind of fall outside of that

00:59:19.740 --> 00:59:20.908
is much harder.

00:59:24.400 --> 00:59:25.560
Thank you all so much.

00:59:25.560 --> 00:59:27.170
It's been really
lovely being here.

00:59:27.170 --> 00:59:28.720
[APPLAUSE]

